title: Grateful Dead Live at Hartford Civic Center on 1990-03-18
lineage: PCM (Sony SL-10) > Sony PCM-601ESD > Behringer Ultramatch Pro >Tascam DA-3000 > Samplitude Pro X3 Suite > FLAC/16
description:
Set 1

Shakedown Street, Little Red Rooster, Stagger Lee, Me & My Uncle-> Mexicali Blues, Friend Of The Devil, Just A Little Light, When I Paint My Masterpiece, Ramble On Rose, The Music Never Stopped

Set 2

Iko Iko, Looks Like Rain-> He's Gone-> Truckin'-> Spoonful-> Drums-> Jam-> The Wheel-> All Along The Watchtower-> Morning Dew, E: U.S. Blues

reviews.review_text:
Flowiest
This show is my favorite, overall, from the Winter/Spring '90 tour. It is matched by 3/29 and maybe by 3/15 or 3/24. Though 3/29 may have the best Second Set and best highlights, this is the tour's best show overall (and this was the most consistent tour as a whole since Spring '77). So, what it doesn't have is whopping best-of-year highlights [though some are close], but it trades that for consistently above-average whole sets, for the flowiest show of the tour. First Set. Actually, the Shakedown opener probably IS the best of '90 [hmmm, seems like there's another great one somewhere, but I see there were only 7...]. Phil carries the bottom - and the top - and the middle! And some people say these aren't good musicians. Ha ha ha ha ha ha. Little Red Rooster was ALWAYS good in '90, but this one still stands out. I'd be standing there, in media res Deadercise, and I'd go "yup they're just gonna stick a blues song in here to play something straightforward for a bit", forgetting again how hot this had been and how much it winds up - and how much I get off. Bobby even avoids mashing his Pups. Jer's 1st solo is slide and his 2nd is MIDI. Check it oot. Stagger Lee is as good as it got - even better than most '78s & '79s. The last minute is way above average. So's the rest of the set, ticking all the boxes. Granted, on Mexicali, Jer plays with his Tijuana Brass MIDI, with mixed results, but his final solo on Friend is a burst of arc plasma. And Just a Little Light (1st of 3 on the tour) is maybe the best ever, fwiw. I'm not sure Ramble is the equal of 3/29, but it's good. Music Never Stopped is the best since 7/17/89, and the second best of the year. Second Set. Another great set opener with Iko Iko, and listen to how Brent plays it this time. Looks Like Rain is polished as a Swiss doorknob, the drums are tight, and Phil again adds bombs and brains. He's Gone isn't the punchiest, but it's slick, and Jer offers to "steal your name" - which is even worse than yr face! Almost as good as 3/21. The whole rest of the set is above average (the Dew is often cited; it's great, but no 3/26). Listen to how Jer starts teasing Spoonful while still blending it perfectly with Truckin'. This may be the best Spoonful of '90, come to think of it. In this era, these eventually sit square on the groove. Right when they think they're handing it to Bill and Mickey, the Devils stop for a minute, and you get a spoonful of psych(edelic). Rather than a short in-and-out Wheel, there's a long build-up. Even though it's not one of the best version of Watchtower (it was a big year for these), it's still great. The only quibble, US Blues is kind of a shy one. 1st Set:  A- 2nd Set: B Overall = 4½ stars Highlights: Shakedown Street - Phil carries Little Red Rooster - wind up and get off Stagger Lee - extension puts it over Just a Little Light - giving Brent due fwiw Music Never Stopped - one of two MNS wins of tour Looks Like Rain - polished as fuck He's Gone - steal your name Spoonful - devilish SOURCES: It goes without saying that you want the 139225_sbd_.miller_truck-mix, else the official release. These are complete, sparkling and correctly pitched - things from which this show long suffered. It's also usually up on YouTube.
